its first round of research research statement dean plummer studies both the physics which govern device operation in silicon integrated circuits and the technology used to fabricate these circuits recent work is aimed at extending silicon device structures into nanoscale dimensions new device concepts are explored through computer simulation and promising ideas are fabricated in the stanford nanofabrication facility to verify ideas experimentally his research also explores the scaling limits of silicon technology and the application of this technology outside traditional integrated circuits last modified thu 1 mar 2012 at 11 25 publications title author s journal date computational prototyping for advanced semiconductor structures james plummer 1995 5 computational prototyping for 21st century semiconductor devices james plummer 1995 8 silicon oxidation kinetics from deal grove to vlsi process models james plummer 1996 5 tcad the semiconductor industry roadmap and a path to the future james plummer 1996 5 silicon ted process simulation whata s possible today and what will be needed tomorrow james plummer 1997 8 computer simulation of silicon technology 1998 10 silicon mosfets conventional and non traditional at the scaling limit james plummer 2000 6 issues in ultra shallow junction fabrication dopant activation and defect kinetics 2001 4 material and process limits in silicon vlsi technology 2001 silicon based devices and technology for the nanoscale era 2004 9 1 of 2 find a faculty member stay connected itunes icon google+ icon facebook icon twitter icon linkedin icon stanford university school of engineering 475 via ortega stanford california 94305 4121 650.725 1575 1997 2012 stanford university all rights reserved accreditation info terms of use copyright complaints contact us
